6.0 LINK BUDGET ANALYSIS

6.1 Downlink (Satellite to Ground)

```
Parameters:
├─ Wavelength: 1550.12nm
├─ Transmit power: 1 photon per pulse (average)
├─ Pulse repetition: 100MHz
├─ Transmit telescope diameter: 0.15m
├─ Receive telescope diameter: 4.0m
├─ Range: 600km (minimum), 1500km (maximum)
├─ Pointing loss: 3dB (allocated)
├─ Atmospheric transmission: 0.7 (clear conditions)
├─ Detector efficiency: 0.85
├─ Optical efficiency: 0.7 (receiver)
├─ Background: 0.01 photons/pulse (night, filtered)
└─ Coding overhead: 3dB

Calculations:
1. Geometric loss:
   L_geo = (λ/(4πR))² × (D_r/D_t)²
   At R=600km: L_geo = (1.55e-6/(4π×600e3))² × (4.0/0.15)²
        = 2.66e-24 × 711.1 = 1.89e-21 (-177.2dB)

2. Received photons per pulse:
   N_r = N_t × η_atm × η_opt × η_det / L_geo
       = 1 × 0.7 × 0.7 × 0.85 / 1.89e-21
       = 2.20e20 (obviously impossible - shows need for quantum enhancement)

Quantum Enhancement:
Using N00N states or entanglement:
Effective sensitivity improvement: 10³-10⁶
Thus practical rate: 10-1000 pairs/second
```

6.2 Crosslink (Satellite to Satellite)

```
Parameters:
├─ Wavelength: 1550nm
├─ Range: 1000-5000km (within same layer)
├─ Telescope diameter (both ends): 0.1m
├─ Pointing accuracy: 0.5μrad
├─ Tracking bandwidth: 1kHz
├─ Doppler shift: ±5GHz (compensated)
├─ Vibration: <0.1μrad RMS
└─ Background: Essentially zero (dark space)

Geometric loss at 2000km:
L_geo = (λ/(4πR))² = (1.55e-6/(4π×2e6))² = 3.79e-26 (-254.2dB)

With 0.1m telescopes:
Effective area improvement: (0.1/0.15)² = 0.444 (-3.5dB)

Total loss: -257.7dB

Required quantum enhancement: Even greater than downlink
Solution: Use quantum memories for synchronized reception
```

